<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-11-11T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-11-11T05:00:00-05:00" n="149" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d149">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">368.117/92: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Capps</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-11-11T12:00:00+02:00"><hi rend="italic">November 11,
                                        1920—noon</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received November 12—3:15
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>246. Legation’s cable number 220, October 15th, 1 p.m. In cases when
                            Greek authorities have seized American passports and have compelled
                            holders to obtain Greek passports in order to return to America can the
                            American consulates in Greece be authorized to visa the Greek passports
                            without extra charge?</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Capps</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>